B.U5=new A.qo(B.N,B.M6,"Key decisions","The calls that shaped the redesign, what drove them, and what we saw.",null)
B.TV=new A.d2("AI features made opt-in on a per-client basis, not globally","Practitioners had strong and varied views on AI in clinical contexts. A single on/off toggle felt too blunt; per-client control let each practitioner calibrate based on their own clinical judgement and the nature of each therapeutic relationship.","Usability session participant responded positively to the granularity. The toggle became a visible signal of practitioner agency, not just a compliance checkbox.",B.bg)
B.U4=new A.d2("Voice assistant outputs shown as editable checklists before execution","Early thinking around voice-first interfaces assumed direct execution would feel faster. Research made clear that practitioners need to see and approve what the system intends to do before it acts \u2014 especially for anything client-facing.","The checklist model removed the core fear of automated errors in clinical communication. Participants described it as the feature that made the voice assistant feel trustworthy rather than risky.",B.bg)
B.o9=new A.z_("Neutral",1,"neutral")
B.TW=new A.d2("Low-contact asynchronous co-design workshop format instead of synchronous sessions","Mental health practitioners have almost no availability for time-intensive research participation. A one-week asynchronous format using Google Workspace tools they already knew lowered the barrier significantly.","Higher participation rate than anticipated. Some delay and occasional confusion about instructions, suggesting that a short synchronous briefing call at the start would improve a future iteration.",B.o9)
B.TO=new A.d2("Focused on practitioner back-office tools, not patient-facing features","Patient-facing mental health apps are a crowded and ethically complex space. Practitioner tools are underrepresented in both the market and in HCI research. The scope decision was both strategic and principled.","Kept the research focused and gave the design a clearer value proposition. The practitioner-as-primary-user framing also produced sharper, more actionable findings than a broader scope would have allowed.",B.bg)
B.LL=s([B.TV,B.U4,B.TW,B.TO],t.qv)
B.U6=new A.qo(B.a6,B.LL,"Key design decisions","Decisions shaped by the tension between capability and trust in a sensitive, high-stakes context.",null)
B.U2=new A.d2("Took pet illnesses and detailed health information out of onboarding entirely","These fields sat early, added real perceived effort, and offered nothing back in the first session. People weren\u2019t invested enough yet to feel it was a fair trade.","A major resistance point disappeared. The information moved to a later in-app prompt, where people had the context and the motivation to give it.",B.bg)
B.TQ=new A.d2("Led with a feature carousel before the first form screen","Both the competitive analysis and the sessions pointed at the same gap \u2014 people had no idea what Perro would do for them before being asked to hand over information.","Tested against a minimal version without it. The carousel did better on engagement and downstream completion, and became the production baseline.",B.bg)
B.TS=new A.d2("Replaced mandatory photo upload with an avatar system and optional image","Sessions showed this was a silent exit trigger. People left to find a suitable photo and frequently didn\u2019t come back, so making it optional removed a low-value blocker.","Drop-off at the dog profile step fell noticeably after launch, and people could finish setup in one sitting without leaving the app.",B.bg)
B.U_=new A.d2("Added a plain-language permissions explainer before the OS prompts","Abrupt system dialogs for location and notifications appeared out of nowhere. Most people either dismissed them or felt ambushed.","Acceptance improved. People who read the explainer were far more likely to grant both location and notification access.",B.bg)
B.TT=new A.d2("Echoed the carousel benefits on the subscription screen","The paywall used to feel disconnected from the onboarding story. Repeating the same four benefit areas tied it back in.","Subscription conversion rose and more people chose longer-term plans. Feedback described the step as feeling \u201cfairer\u201d and \u201cmore honest\u201d.",B.bg)
B.U3=new A.d2("Moved activity level and some fitness questions to post-signup prompts","They were arriving when people were already fatigued, and before they\u2019d done anything in the app that made the questions feel relevant.","Late-funnel fatigue dropped. The information still gets collected, just at a point where people have a reason to care about it.",B.bg)
